x4freetext: The 4He target gas was contained in a 9.7-cm-diam
cell with a team-entrance snout about 6-cm long. A
beam-entrance aperture on the snout, and a
cell opening through which the beam and detected
Each of two detector assemblies, left and
right of the beam direction, consisted of a stack of
behind a standard gas-target collimator arrangement.
The 17- and 150-microm detectors were used to
perform DE-E mass identification of the a-particles
The laboratory cross sections were computed from the
where Y is the number (yield) of scattered particles
(corrected for background and dead time), theta0 is
the laboratory scattering angle, n is the number of
beam particles, N is the number of target particles
per unit volume, and G is the gas-target geometry
factor. For the symmetric geometry, the yield is the
average of the yield of the left and right detectors.
Cross sections are not quoted for theta(c.m.) = 25
intercepted some of the beam leaving the gas target.
The data analysis was conducted with an
by F.D. Correll. This code derives from the Zurich
code EINSNUL and uses the minimization program MINUIT.

x4freetext: The total relative cross section error was
expected to be equal the statistical error plus 1.0
percent, but it became apparent, even with a small
statistical error, that an unknown systematic error
was dominating the relative error. A careful study of
this systematic error resulted in the assignment of a
relative error of +-2.0 percent for triton detection
